scale from where 1 = not at all characteristic, 2 = somewhat uncharacteristic, 3 = neither characteristic nor uncharacteristic, 4 = somewhat characteristic, and 5 =
very characteristic. Higher scores indicate more secure attachment style. 
Trait Anxiety. We will measure trait anxiety using the same strategies as Popper and Amit (2009) in using the STAI for adults.  Respondents will be provided the
following instructions:  “Read each statement and then blacken the appropriate circle to the right of the statement to indicate how you feel right now, that is, at
this moment. There are no right or wrong answers. Do not spend too much time on any one statement but give the answer which seems to describe your
present feelings best.” They will then indicate their responses from 1 = Not at all, 2 = Somewhat, 3 = Moderately so, and 4 = Very much so. Higher scores indicate
higher trait anxiety.
Openness to Experiences. Similar to the attachment style scale, Popper and Amit (2009) did not supply the items they used for their openness to new
experiences scale. They disclosed they used an abbreviated version of the NEO-PI-R openness to experience scale consisting of 24 items. We cannot know the
specific items Popper and Amit (2009) used for their study; however, the International Personality Item Pool (IPIP) has 20-item abbreviated NEO Openness to
Experience measure that is commonly used in social science research. Thus, we will use this version of the NEO Openness to Experience measure. The following
instructions will be given to participants “Describe yourself as you generally are now, not as you wish to be in the future. Describe yourself as you honestly see
yourself, in relation to other people you know of the same sex as you are, and roughly your same age. So that you can describe yourself in an honest manner,
your responses will be kept in absolute confidence. Indicate for each statement whether it is 1. Very Inaccurate, 2. Moderately Inaccurate, 3. Neither Accurate Nor
Inaccurate, 4. Moderately Accurate, or 5. Very Accurate as a description of you.” Higher scores indicate higher Openness to Experience.
Leadership Experiences. We will measure leadership experiences using the same strategies as Popper and Amit (2009). The scale used for this construct was
created by Popper and Amit (2009) specifically for their study, and was designed to capture the early-life experiences with influence and leadership roles of
participants prior to their joining the military. Popper and Amit provided the questions for the scale. As such, participants will be asked to read a set of seven
statements about their past leadership experiences and rate each statement regarding the level of experience they have with each. Popper and Amit did not
provide instructions for their scale, however, so we created instructions to ensure participants are reflecting on their experiences through high school and prior
to joining the military, which is consistent with the desired time period put forth by Popper and Amit for this scale. Participants will see the instructions, “ For the
following statements, please think about your early life experiences through grade school education and up to high school graduation (i.e., prior to joining the
military). Please select the answer below that best describes the extent of experience you had with the topic in each statement during this early life time period.”
Items will be rated on a scale of 1 to 4 where 1 = Hardly any experience, 2 = Some experience, 3 = Moderate experience, and 4 = Rich experience. Popper and
Amit (2009) only suppled the scale anchors at 1 and 4 for this measure, so we had to create the response options for 2 and 3. Higher scores indicate greater
extent of early leadership experience.
